{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774639234,"nonce":"+HzcQzqPbSjibmBB1yLJC95ryq0=","message":"## Spec: Modal Serverless GPU Integration for feedbax Training\n\n### 1. Architecture Overview\n\nThe wrapper lives in `src/rlrmp/modal_runner.py` (with a potential future extraction to feedbax). It provides a generic mechanism for running **any** feedbax/rlrmp training script on Modal GPUs, with `.map()` support for distributing sweep conditions across parallel GPU containers.\n\n**Core design principle**: The wrapper does NOT import or modify training scripts. It runs them as subprocesses (like you would on a remote machine), collecting results from the output directory. This means zero changes to existing scripts.\n\n```\nrlrmp/\n  src/rlrmp/\n    modal_runner.py          # Modal app definition + image + runner functions\n    modal_config.py          # GPU type aliases, default configs\n  scripts/\n    modal_sweep.py           # CLI entry point for launching sweeps\n    modal_train.py           # CLI entry point for single runs\n```\n\n### 2. Modal Image Definition\n\nThe image must include: JAX with CUDA, feedbax, rlrmp, jax-cookbook (private, not on PyPI), and all transitive dependencies.\n\n**Key challenge**: feedbax, rlrmp, and jax-cookbook are all private repos (github.com/i-m-mll/*). Two modes are needed:\n\n**Mode A — Dev mode (local mount)**: Mount local source trees into the container at startup. Fast iteration, no image rebuild needed for code changes. Uses `add_local_python_source`.\n\n**Mode B — Pinned mode (git install)**: Install from specific git commits via GitHub deploy keys stored in `modal.Secret`. Reproducible, suitable for \"production\" sweeps. Uses `pip_install_private_repos` or `pip_install` with git+ssh URLs.\n\n```python\nimport modal\n\napp = modal.App(\"feedbax-training\")\n\n# --- Secrets for private repo access (pinned mode) ---\ngithub_secret = modal.Secret.from_name(\"github-deploy-key\")\n\n# --- Volumes ---\nresults_vol = modal.Volume.from_name(\"feedbax-results\", create_if_missing=True)\njax_cache_vol = modal.Volume.from_name(\"jax-compilation-cache\", create_if_missing=True)\n\n\ndef build_image(\n    gpu: str = \"A10G\",\n    dev_mode: bool = True,\n    feedbax_ref: str = \"main\",\n    rlrmp_ref: str = \"main\",\n    jax_cookbook_ref: str = \"main\",\n) -\u003e modal.Image:\n    \"\"\"Build the training image.\n\n    Args:\n        gpu: GPU type string (determines CUDA version).\n        dev_mode: If True, mount local source trees instead of installing from git.\n        feedbax_ref: Git ref for feedbax (branch/tag/commit). Ignored in dev_mode.\n        rlrmp_ref: Git ref for rlrmp. Ignored in dev_mode.\n        jax_cookbook_ref: Git ref for jax-cookbook. Ignored in dev_mode.\n    \"\"\"\n    img = (\n        modal.Image.debian_slim(python_version=\"3.12\")\n        .apt_install(\"git\")\n        .pip_install(\n            \"jax[cuda12]\",\n            \"equinox\u003e=0.11.12\",\n            \"diffrax\u003e=0.7.0\",\n            \"jaxtyping\u003e=0.2.38\",\n            \"optax\u003e=0.2.4\",\n            \"matplotlib\u003e=3.10.1\",\n            \"numpy\u003e=2.2.3\",\n            \"plotly\u003e=6.0.0\",\n            \"polars\u003e=1.24.0\",\n            \"seaborn\u003e=0.13.2\",\n            \"tensorboardx\u003e=2.6.2.2\",\n            \"tqdm\u003e=4.67.1\",\n            \"crc32c\u003e=2.7.1\",\n            \"statsmodels\u003e=0.14.5\",\n            \"ipywidgets\u003e=8.1.8\",\n            gpu=gpu,  # ensure CUDA-compatible wheels\n        )\n        .env({\n            \"JAX_COMPILATION_CACHE_DIR\": \"/cache/jax\",\n            \"XLA_FLAGS\": \"--xla_gpu_deterministic_ops=false\",\n        })\n    )\n\n    if dev_mode:\n        # Mount local source trees — changes propagate without image rebuild.\n        # These are added at container startup (copy=False by default).\n        img = (\n            img\n            .add_local_python_source(\"jax_cookbook\")\n            .add_local_python_source(\"feedbax\")\n            .add_local_python_source(\"rlrmp\")\n        )\n    else:\n        # Install from pinned git refs via GitHub deploy key.\n        # Requires a Modal Secret named \"github-deploy-key\" with SSH_PRIVATE_KEY.\n        img = img.pip_install(\n            f\"jax-cookbook @ git+ssh://git@github.com/i-m-mll/jax-cookbook.git@{jax_cookbook_ref}\",\n            f\"feedbax @ git+ssh://git@github.com/i-m-mll/feedbax.git@{feedbax_ref}\",\n            f\"rlrmp @ git+ssh://git@github.com/i-m-mll/rlrmp.git@{rlrmp_ref}\",\n            secrets=[github_secret],\n        )\n\n    return img\n\n\n# Default image (dev mode, A10G)\ndefault_image = build_image(dev_mode=True, gpu=\"A10G\")\n```\n\n### 3. Runner Function\n\n```python\nimport json\nimport os\nimport shutil\nimport subprocess\nimport tarfile\nimport tempfile\nfrom pathlib import Path\nfrom typing import Any\n\nRESULTS_MOUNT = \"/results\"\nCACHE_MOUNT = \"/cache\"\n\n\n@app.function(\n    image=default_image,\n    gpu=\"A10G\",\n    timeout=7200,  # 2 hours max per condition\n    volumes={\n        RESULTS_MOUNT: results_vol,\n        CACHE_MOUNT: jax_cache_vol,\n    },\n)\ndef run_training(\n    script_path: str,\n    args: dict[str, Any],\n    run_id: str,\n) -\u003e dict[str, Any]:\n    \"\"\"Run a training script with the given arguments.\n\n    Args:\n        script_path: Relative path to the training script\n            (e.g. \"scripts/train_minimax.py\" or \"scripts/train_part2_5.py\").\n        args: Dictionary of CLI arguments. Keys are argument names\n            (without leading --), values are argument values.\n            Example: {\"n-warmup-batches\": 2000, \"output-dir\": \"/tmp/run\"}\n        run_id: Unique identifier for this run (used for result collection).\n\n    Returns:\n        Dictionary with:\n            - \"status\": \"success\" or \"error\"\n            - \"output_dir\": Path where results were written\n            - \"run_id\": The run_id that was passed in\n            - \"duration_seconds\": Wall-clock time\n            - \"gpu_info\": nvidia-smi output\n            - \"files\": List of output files\n            - \"error\": Error message (if status == \"error\")\n    \"\"\"\n    import time\n\n    start = time.monotonic()\n\n    # Capture GPU info\n    gpu_info = subprocess.run(\n        [\"nvidia-smi\", \"--query-gpu=name,memory.total,memory.free\",\n         \"--format=csv,noheader\"],\n        capture_output=True, text=True,\n    ).stdout.strip()\n\n    # Build the output directory inside the results volume\n    output_dir = f\"{RESULTS_MOUNT}/{run_id}\"\n    os.makedirs(output_dir, exist_ok=True)\n\n    # Override output-dir in args\n    args = {**args, \"output-dir\": output_dir}\n\n    # Also set JAX cache dir\n    args.setdefault(\"jax-cache-dir\", f\"{CACHE_MOUNT}/jax\")\n\n    # Build CLI command\n    cmd = [\"python\", script_path]\n    for key, value in args.items():\n        flag = f\"--{key}\"\n        if isinstance(value, bool):\n            if value:\n                cmd.append(flag)\n            else:\n                cmd.append(f\"--no-{key.replace(chr(45), chr(45))}\")\n        else:\n            cmd.extend([flag, str(value)])\n\n    # Run the training script\n    result = subprocess.run(\n        cmd,\n        capture_output=True,\n        text=True,\n        env={**os.environ, \"JAX_COMPILATION_CACHE_DIR\": f\"{CACHE_MOUNT}/jax\"},\n    )\n\n    duration = time.monotonic() - start\n\n    # Commit volume changes so results persist\n    results_vol.commit()\n    jax_cache_vol.commit()\n\n    # Collect output file list\n    output_files = []\n    for root, dirs, files in os.walk(output_dir):\n        for f in files:\n            fp = os.path.join(root, f)\n            rel = os.path.relpath(fp, output_dir)\n            size = os.path.getsize(fp)\n            output_files.append({\"path\": rel, \"size_bytes\": size})\n\n    if result.returncode != 0:\n        return {\n            \"status\": \"error\",\n            \"run_id\": run_id,\n            \"output_dir\": output_dir,\n            \"duration_seconds\": duration,\n            \"gpu_info\": gpu_info,\n            \"files\": output_files,\n            \"error\": result.stderr[-2000:],  # last 2KB of stderr\n            \"stdout_tail\": result.stdout[-2000:],\n        }\n\n    return {\n        \"status\": \"success\",\n        \"run_id\": run_id,\n        \"output_dir\": output_dir,\n        \"duration_seconds\": duration,\n        \"gpu_info\": gpu_info,\n        \"files\": output_files,\n    }\n\n\n@app.function(\n    image=default_image,\n    volumes={RESULTS_MOUNT: results_vol},\n    timeout=300,\n)\ndef download_results(run_id: str) -\u003e bytes:\n    \"\"\"Download results for a run as a tar.gz archive.\n\n    Args:\n        run_id: The run_id to download results for.\n\n    Returns:\n        tar.gz bytes of the output directory.\n    \"\"\"\n    import io\n    results_vol.reload()\n    output_dir = f\"{RESULTS_MOUNT}/{run_id}\"\n    buf = io.BytesIO()\n    with tarfile.open(fileobj=buf, mode=\"w:gz\") as tar:\n        tar.add(output_dir, arcname=run_id)\n    return buf.getvalue()\n```\n\n### 4. Sweep Runner (`.map()` parallelism)\n\n```python\n@app.function(\n    image=default_image,\n    timeout=14400,  # 4 hours for full sweep coordination\n)\ndef run_sweep(\n    script_path: str,\n    sweep_configs: list[dict[str, Any]],\n    sweep_name: str,\n    gpu: str = \"A10G\",\n) -\u003e list[dict[str, Any]]:\n    \"\"\"Run a parameter sweep across multiple GPU containers.\n\n    Args:\n        script_path: Path to the training script.\n        sweep_configs: List of arg dicts, one per condition.\n        sweep_name: Human-readable name for the sweep.\n        gpu: GPU type to use for each condition.\n\n    Returns:\n        List of result dicts from run_training.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Generate run_ids\n    import hashlib\n    run_ids = []\n    for i, config in enumerate(sweep_configs):\n        config_hash = hashlib.md5(\n            json.dumps(config, sort_keys=True).encode()\n        ).hexdigest()[:8]\n        run_ids.append(f\"{sweep_name}/{i:02d}_{config_hash}\")\n\n    # Launch all conditions in parallel via .starmap()\n    results = list(run_training.starmap(\n        [(script_path, config, rid)\n         for config, rid in zip(sweep_configs, run_ids)],\n        return_exceptions=True,\n    ))\n\n    return results\n```\n\n### 5. Local CLI Entry Point\n\n```python\n# scripts/modal_sweep.py\n\"\"\"Launch a ratio sweep on Modal.\n\nUsage:\n    # Dev mode (mount local code):\n    modal run scripts/modal_sweep.py --sweep ratio\n\n    # Pinned mode (install from git):\n    modal run scripts/modal_sweep.py --sweep ratio --pinned --ref main\n\"\"\"\nimport modal\nfrom rlrmp.modal_runner import app, run_sweep, download_results\n\nRATIO_SWEEP_CONDITIONS = [\n    # baseline (no loss update)\n    {\n        \"loss-mode\": \"running_cost\",\n        \"training-method\": \"standard\",\n        \"pert-std\": 1.0,\n        \"n-batches\": 10000,\n        \"enable-loss-update\": False,\n    },\n    # r=0.1 through r=0.6\n    *[\n        {\n            \"loss-mode\": \"running_cost\",\n            \"training-method\": \"standard\",\n            \"pert-std\": 1.0,\n            \"n-batches\": 10000,\n            \"enable-loss-update\": True,\n            \"target-ratio\": r / 10,\n        }\n        for r in range(1, 7)\n    ],\n]\n\n\n@app.local_entrypoint()\ndef main(\n    sweep: str = \"ratio\",\n    gpu: str = \"A10G\",\n    download: bool = True,\n    local_dir: str = \"results/modal_sweep\",\n):\n    if sweep == \"ratio\":\n        configs = RATIO_SWEEP_CONDITIONS\n        script = \"scripts/train_part2_5.py\"\n    else:\n        raise ValueError(f\"Unknown sweep: {sweep}\")\n\n    print(f\"Launching {len(configs)} conditions on {gpu} GPUs...\")\n    results = run_sweep.remote(\n        script_path=script,\n        sweep_configs=configs,\n        sweep_name=sweep,\n        gpu=gpu,\n    )\n\n    # Print summary\n    for r in results:\n        if isinstance(r, Exception):\n            print(f\"  FAILED: {r}\")\n        else:\n            status = r[\"status\"]\n            dur = r[\"duration_seconds\"]\n            rid = r[\"run_id\"]\n            print(f\"  {rid}: {status} ({dur:.0f}s)\")\n\n    # Download results locally\n    if download:\n        import os\n        os.makedirs(local_dir, exist_ok=True)\n        for r in results:\n            if isinstance(r, Exception) or r[\"status\"] != \"success\":\n                continue\n            rid = r[\"run_id\"]\n            print(f\"Downloading {rid}...\")\n            tar_bytes = download_results.remote(rid)\n            tar_path = os.path.join(local_dir, f\"{rid.replace(chr(47), chr(95))}.tar.gz\")\n            os.makedirs(os.path.dirname(tar_path), exist_ok=True)\n            with open(tar_path, \"wb\") as f:\n                f.write(tar_bytes)\n            print(f\"  Saved to {tar_path}\")\n```\n\n### 6. Cost Analysis\n\n#### Current RunPod Workflow\n- **Hardware**: 2x RTX 4090 (24 GB VRAM each), spot at ~$0.34/GPU/hr = $0.68/hr total\n- **Workflow**: SSH in, manual setup, run 8 conditions sequentially on 2 GPUs (4 rounds)\n- **Time**: ~10-15 min per condition (train_part2_5 with 10k batches) = ~60-75 min for 8 conditions (4 serial rounds of 2 parallel)\n- **Typical cost**: ~$0.68/hr x 1.25hr = **~$0.85 per sweep** (compute only)\n- **But**: idle time before/after, setup time, risk of spot preemption mid-sweep, manual scp for results\n\nFor adversarial training (train_minimax.py):\n- **Time**: ~15-20 min per condition (2k warmup + 8k adversarial batches), single-condition runs\n- **Typical cost**: $0.34/hr x 0.3hr = **~$0.10 per condition** (single GPU)\n\n#### Modal Pricing (per condition, ~700 MB VRAM, ~5 GB RAM per run)\n\n| GPU Type | $/hr | Est. time/cond | Cost/cond | 8-cond sweep | vs RunPod |\n|----------|------|----------------|-----------|--------------|-----------|\n| T4 (16 GB) | $0.59 | ~18 min | $0.18 | $1.44 | 1.7x more |\n| L4 (24 GB) | $0.80 | ~12 min | $0.16 | $1.28 | 1.5x more |\n| A10G (24 GB) | $1.10 | ~10 min | $0.18 | $1.47 | 1.7x more |\n| A100 40 GB | $2.10 | ~8 min | $0.28 | $2.24 | 2.6x more |\n| A100 80 GB | $2.50 | ~8 min | $0.33 | $2.67 | 3.1x more |\n| H100 (80 GB) | $3.95 | ~6 min | $0.40 | $3.16 | 3.7x more |\n\n**Notes on time estimates**:\n- T4: ~1.5x slower than RTX 4090 (older arch, lower bandwidth)\n- L4: ~1.2x slower than RTX 4090 (Ada Lovelace but lower clocks)\n- A10G: ~similar to RTX 4090 for this workload (small model, compute not memory bound)\n- A100/H100: faster XLA compilation, slightly faster training, but the workload is too small to fully utilize the hardware advantage\n\n**The critical comparison is not $/condition but total wall-clock time**:\n\n| Scenario | Wall-clock | Total cost | Convenience |\n|----------|-----------|------------|-------------|\n| RunPod 2x4090 spot (serial) | ~60-75 min | ~$0.85 | Low (manual SSH, scp, fragile setup) |\n| Modal 8x A10G (parallel) | ~10-12 min | ~$1.47 | High (one command, automatic results) |\n| Modal 8x L4 (parallel) | ~12-15 min | ~$1.28 | High |\n| Modal 8x T4 (parallel) | ~18-22 min | ~$1.44 | High |\n\n**Cost overhead for Modal**: ~$0.50-$1.80 more per sweep, but:\n- Eliminates 10-15 min manual setup time\n- Eliminates spot preemption risk (pay-per-second, no idle)\n- Results returned programmatically (no scp)\n- Reproducible environment (no \"pip install broke on restart\")\n- 4-6x faster wall-clock for full sweep\n- $30/mo free credits on starter plan covers ~20-25 sweeps on L4\n\n**Recommendation**: L4 is the sweet spot. Cheapest per-sweep, good performance for small models, and the 24 GB VRAM provides headroom for larger experiments.\n\n### 7. JAX Compilation Cache Strategy\n\nJAX compilation is the dominant cold-start cost. First run on a new image compiles all XLA kernels (~2-5 min). Subsequent runs with the same model architecture skip compilation entirely.\n\n**Strategy**: Persist the JAX compilation cache to a Modal Volume (`jax-compilation-cache`), mounted at `/cache/jax`. Set `JAX_COMPILATION_CACHE_DIR=/cache/jax` in the image environment.\n\n- First sweep: +2-5 min compilation overhead per unique model architecture\n- Subsequent sweeps with same architecture: near-zero compilation overhead\n- Different architectures (e.g., changing hidden_size, n_replicates) will trigger fresh compilation\n- The cache volume persists across runs indefinitely\n\nThe `--jax-cache-dir` flag is already supported by `train_minimax.py` and can be added trivially to `train_part2_5.py`.\n\n### 8. Migration Plan\n\n**Phase 1 — Minimal viable wrapper (this issue)**\n1. Create `src/rlrmp/modal_runner.py` with image definition + `run_training` function\n2. Create `scripts/modal_train.py` for single runs\n3. Create `scripts/modal_sweep.py` for ratio sweep\n4. Add `modal` to rlrmp dev dependencies\n5. Set up Modal account + secrets (github-deploy-key)\n6. Test with `train_part2_5.py` ratio sweep (7 conditions, L4 GPUs)\n7. Test with `train_minimax.py` single run\n\n**Phase 2 — Polish**\n1. Add `download_results` function for fetching results to local machine\n2. Add progress monitoring (poll Modal dashboard or use webhooks)\n3. Add `--jax-cache-dir` support to `train_part2_5.py`\n4. Validate JAX compilation cache persistence across runs\n\n**Phase 3 — Optional future work**\n1. Extract generic wrapper to feedbax (if useful for non-rlrmp experiments)\n2. Support Modal `Cls` for long-lived training servers (interactive debugging)\n3. Support checkpointing + resume across Modal container restarts\n4. Integration with feedbax studio for live loss curve visualization\n\n### 9. What Changes vs What Stays the Same\n\n**Stays the same:**\n- All training scripts (train_minimax.py, train_part2_5.py) — zero modifications\n- All eval scripts — run locally as before (they analyze saved results)\n- Output format — same .eqx files, .npz files, config.json\n- CLI arguments — identical, just passed via dict instead of command line\n\n**Changes:**\n- Launch command: `modal run scripts/modal_sweep.py --sweep ratio` instead of SSH + manual\n- Results location: downloaded from Modal Volume to `results/modal_sweep/` instead of scp\n- Environment: deterministic Docker image instead of manually pip-installed pod\n- Parallelism: automatic via `.starmap()` instead of manual tmux sessions\n\n### 10. Open Questions and Tradeoffs\n\n1. **Dev mode dependency resolution**: `add_local_python_source` mounts source trees but does not install their dependencies. The image `pip_install` step must explicitly list all transitive deps. This is fragile if feedbax/rlrmp deps change. Alternative: build a requirements.txt from `uv pip compile` and use `pip_install_from_requirements`.\n\n2. **jax-cookbook distribution**: Currently private and not on PyPI. Options: (a) mount as local source in dev mode, (b) install from private git in pinned mode, (c) publish to PyPI (simplest long-term). Publishing would also simplify feedbax's own dependency chain.\n\n3. **Warm pool strategy**: Modal's `min_containers=0` (default) means every run starts cold. For iterative development, setting `min_containers=1` keeps a warm GPU but costs ~$1.10/hr (A10G) even when idle. Probably not worth it for batch training workloads.\n\n4. **Container timeout**: Training scripts can take 15-60 min. Modal's default timeout may be too short. The `timeout=7200` (2hr) in the spec should cover all current workloads, but adversarial training with large batch counts may need more.\n\n5. **Result persistence**: Modal Volumes are persistent but have limits (~50k files for v1). For long-running projects with many sweeps, periodic cleanup or switching to Volumes v2 (beta, unlimited files) may be needed.\n\n6. **CUDA version**: Modal ships CUDA driver 13.0 with host driver 580.x. The `jax[cuda12]` pip install should be compatible (CUDA 12.x userspace on 13.x driver). Verify on first run.\n\n7. **Data transfer costs**: Results are small (~10-50 MB per condition: .eqx model files + loss curves). Not a concern for cost, but download_results adds a round-trip.\n\n8. **Feedbax plugin system**: rlrmp registers itself as a feedbax plugin via `[project.entry-points.\"feedbax.plugins\"]`. In dev mode (source mount), this entry point is not installed. Need to verify that the training scripts do not rely on plugin discovery — they import rlrmp directly, so this should be fine.\n\n9. **Script path resolution**: The `run_training` function receives a relative script path (e.g., \"scripts/train_minimax.py\"). In dev mode, rlrmp's source is mounted but not its scripts directory. Either: (a) mount the scripts dir explicitly, (b) use absolute paths based on a known mount point, or (c) include scripts in the image. Option (a) is simplest.\n\nCo-authored-by: Claude Opus 4.6 \u003cnoreply@anthropic.com\u003e","files":null}]}